  <section class="trust-bar"><div class="wrap"><span>Licensed · Insured</span><span>Same-day · 5 SoCal counties</span><span>$120 commercial diagnostic · waived with repair</span></div></section>

  <section class="section"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>Speed Queen — 1908, Alliance, employee-owned</h2>
    <p>Speed Queen is the flagship commercial brand of Alliance Laundry Systems, headquartered in Ripon, Wisconsin. Alliance has been employee-owned through an ESOP (employee stock ownership plan) since July 2018, when BDT Capital Partners and the employees acquired the company from Kohlberg Kravis Roberts. The ESOP structure is the operational signature of the company — engineering priorities are set by employee-owners rather than being subordinated to a multi-brand conglomerate's annual integration cycle. For LA operators used to seeing commercial equipment brands folded into Ali Group, ITW, Middleby, or Welbilt portfolios, Alliance's employee-ownership is distinctive — and it shows up in the product.</p>
    <p>Speed Queen itself dates to 1908, which makes it the oldest continuously-operating commercial laundry brand in North America. Huebsch (an Alliance sibling) is actually older — 1887 — but Speed Queen has the larger US install base and dominates the US laundromat + OPL specification. In LA specifically, Speed Queen is the default new-laundromat specification and the most common mid-to-upper hotel OPL spec; competing brands (Dexter, Continental Girbau, Wascomat) turn up in specific niches but Alliance-family dominates the overall install count.</p>
    <p>The Alliance family single-call is a real operational value for multi-property operators. Speed Queen (flagship laundromat + OPL), UniMac (heavy-duty industrial — tier above Speed Queen), Huebsch (OPL mid-market + small-format laundromat, 1887 heritage), IPSO (international / overseas-hospitality), Primus (European OPL), and Laundrylux (distributor) all route parts + dispatch through Ripon WI shared infrastructure. Our Alliance-family service spans Speed Queen + UniMac + Huebsch combo coverage in LA; if you have a mixed Alliance install, one call covers the room.</p>
  </div></section>

  <section class="section alt"><div class="wrap">
    <h2>Speed Queen Commercial models we service</h2>
    <div class="model-grid">
      <div class="model-card"><h3>SQFA7 — top-load OPL / laundromat</h3><p>Speed Queen's signature top-load commercial washer. Shows up at mid-scale laundromats and hotel OPL. Service domain: coin mechanism (coin variant), door interlock, water-inlet valve, drive belt, drain pump, agitator seal.</p></div>
      <div class="model-card"><h3>SFNNCA — front-load OPL / soft-mount</h3><p>Commercial front-load with VFD inverter drive for extraction-speed control. Laundromat and OPL standard on the Alliance front-load side. Service focus: inverter drive diagnostics, door gasket, door interlock, main motor bearings, drain pump.</p></div>
      <div class="model-card"><h3>SFTX / STTS / STGS — stack washer / dryer</h3><p>Vertical stack configuration for space-constrained LA laundry rooms — apartment laundry, hotel OPL, and fitness-center installs. Stack variants include washer-over-dryer and dryer-over-dryer configurations. Service spans both the washer and dryer sections with shared parts.</p></div>
      <div class="model-card"><h3>SDGS / STGS — single-pocket commercial dryer</h3><p>Single-pocket gas or electric commercial dryer. OPL workhorse. Service: gas valve, ignitor, flame sensor, burner assembly (gas models); heating element (electric); door switch, blower motor, belt, lint trap / duct pressure switch across both.</p></div>
      <div class="model-card"><h3>TR-series — tumbler / OPL high-volume</h3><p>High-volume tumbler dryer. Hotel + hospital central-laundry standard. Heavier capacity than SDGS. Service: larger-scale versions of SDGS components, plus steam-coil diagnostics where steam-heated variants installed.</p></div>
      <div class="model-card"><h3>TTI / TTE — industrial top-load</h3><p>Industrial duty-cycle top-load washer for heavy OPL and linen-rental processors. Heavier bearings, commercial-grade shocks, specified for 30,000+ cycle life. Service paths extend the SQFA7 domain with industrial-grade part replacements.</p></div>
      <div class="model-card"><h3>LTSA — coin-op laundromat flagship</h3><p>Speed Queen's coin-op top-load laundromat flagship. LTSA is the single densest model in LA laundromat coverage. Coin mechanism + coin slide + vandalism repair + card-reader retrofit work all live here.</p></div>
      <div class="model-card"><h3>Coin mechanism and card-reader integration</h3><p>Speed Queen coin variants interface with ESD, Card Concepts, and comparable card-reader systems for laundromat operators converting from pure coin to card + app payment. We service the mechanical side; card-system integration is a coordinated project with the card vendor.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>

  <section class="section"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>LA laundromat cluster — where Speed Queen concentrates</h2>
    <p>The LA laundromat market runs Speed Queen as default specification. Launderland's multi-site chain across LA County and the South Bay, Dadson Laundry's operations across Koreatown and Mid-Wilshire, plus independent laundromats throughout East LA, South LA, Pico-Union, Koreatown, Hollywood, and the broader working-class LA corridors — all Speed Queen-heavy. Our densest single-model coverage is LTSA coin-op top-loads; most LA laundromats run 20–60 LTSA units plus 15–30 front-loads and a matching dryer bank.</p>
    <p>Typical laundromat call pattern in our LA coverage: coin mechanism jams from bent quarters or transit tokens (routine cleaning + realignment); door interlock failures on LTSA from cumulative lid-slam wear; drain pump clogs from customer neglect of pocket-check (socks, coins, fabric bits); water-inlet valve failures tracking the LA hard-water scale pattern; drive belt wear on belt-driven variants; and inverter drive faults on SFNNCA front-loads after brownouts. We stock common Speed Queen LTSA and SFNNCA service parts on the truck for single-visit resolution where possible; specialty parts route 1–3 day through Alliance's LA-area distributor channel.</p>
    <p>The Alliance family single-call matters at laundromat scale — operators running mixed Speed Queen + UniMac + Huebsch rooms get one dispatch covering the whole room. Speed Queen + Huebsch is the common laundromat pairing (Speed Queen washers + Huebsch HC coin-op dryers); Speed Queen + UniMac is more common in industrial and large-hotel OPL.</p>
  </div></section>

  <section class="section alt"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>LA hotel + hospital OPL — the other major Speed Queen vertical</h2>
    <p>On-premises laundry (OPL) at LA luxury hotels and hospitals is the second major vertical where Speed Queen Commercial concentrates. Specific installations where we service Speed Queen regularly: Ritz-Carlton DTLA central laundry, Cedars-Sinai medical-center linen processing, Kaiser Permanente multi-campus OPL (Sunset Boulevard, West LA, Panorama City, Downey), plus comparable mid-to-upper hotel properties with in-house linen + staff-uniform processing (Waldorf Astoria Beverly Hills, Peninsula Beverly Hills, Four Seasons, JW Marriott DTLA).</p>
    <p>OPL Speed Queen runs on different duty cycles than laundromat units — substantially heavier daily usage, tighter uptime requirements, and integration with chemical-injection systems for medical-grade linen processing. The SDGS single-pocket dryer and TR-series tumbler are the core OPL dryer specifications; TTI / TTE industrial top-loads handle the washer side at higher-volume properties. When a hotel or hospital OPL Speed Queen dryer goes down, linen shortage cascades into the housekeeping or nursing operation within 12 hours — we prioritize these calls as same-day emergency-class dispatch.</p>
    <p>Multi-housing is the third Speed Queen vertical worth calling out: large apartment complexes, student-housing operations, and senior-living facilities across Koreatown, East LA, Westwood (student density), and senior-living campuses in the Valley. The laundry-room model at these properties is typically card-reader or card + app payment (not coin anymore at newer installs), with SFNNCA front-loads + STTS/STGS stack units dominating. Service patterns overlap the laundromat call mix with lower overall call density per location.</p>
  </div></section>

  <section class="section"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>What breaks — inverter drive, coin mechanism, bearings</h2>
    <p>Across our Speed Queen Commercial service volume, three failure domains concentrate most of the call work.</p>
    <p><b>Inverter drive faults</b> sit on the front-load SFNNCA and stack-front-load variants. After LA brownouts or hard shutoffs mid-cycle, the VFD on the main motor can throw an overcurrent trip on restart, a communication loss with the control panel, or a voltage-sag detection lockout. Diagnostic sequence: read fault on panel; cycle main disconnect for full drive reset; tighten drive-to-motor output connections; verify voltage-sag threshold isn't over-tight for LA brownout conditions; test motor winding resistance. Most fault calls resolve with reset + tightening + threshold adjustment; drive replacement only needed roughly 10–15% of the time.</p>
    <p><b>Coin mechanism wear</b> concentrates on LTSA coin-op laundromat units and coin-variant SFNNCA. Coin drops jam from bent coins, transit tokens (Metro Transit tokens sized close to quarter dimensions jam Koreatown and East LA laundromats routinely), and accumulated grit. Coin slide mechanisms fail from cycling wear after several thousand uses. Vandalism repair is periodic but predictable at specific laundromats; we stock common replacement slides. Card-reader retrofits are coordinated projects with card-system vendors like ESD or Card Concepts.</p>
    <p><b>Bearing and drum wear</b> is the long-term failure mode on high-cycle-count SFNNCA front-loads and TTI industrial top-loads. Drum bearings at 30,000+ cycle life typically need rebuild somewhere in the 7–10 year range of heavy laundromat duty; rumbling or vibration at spin extraction is the early signal. Catching bearing wear early is a $600–$1,000 rebuild; running it to catastrophic failure damages the drum and shaft and escalates to $1,400–$2,200.</p>
  </div></section>

  <section class="section alt"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>What Speed Queen Commercial repair costs in LA</h2>
    <p>$120 flat commercial diagnostic, waived with repair.</p>
